Parliament has not ratified the amendment to free Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, as part of a criminal law amendment, a proposal to cancel the paragraph on the indictment of opposition leader Julia Tymosenko.
MEPs rejected the amendment to reduce the penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the door to freedom for the former Prime Minister, now imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to seven years in prison for entering into a supposedly disadvantageous deal with Russia to buy natural gas.
The verdict is not final and the court is expected to rule on the convict's appeal in December.
Tymosenko calls the verdict political revenge by the regime and has provoked a process of suspicion of bias by the court also in the West.
The bill to repeal Section 365 of the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MPs.
It would have taken 226 votes to pass.
