The diet of an obese child: not eating breakfast and eating meat for dinner
More than one third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, 9% of schoolchildren are overweight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This again shows how important the environment and the patterns that surround us are.
For example, the number of meals on the tables of obese children is 50 percent higher than in families with normal-weight children.
19% of obese people had French fries for dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In families with small children, sports are also not a habit, as is now the case with most schoolchildren today - only 15% said that at least once a week parents found time for active exercise.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out during the last school year and involved 900 pupils in primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", a campaign supported by the General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since its inception, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third grade have signed up for this project.
One of the key factors in the dramatic increase in the number of overweight and obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and exercise.
"Only half of the children surveyed say they eat breakfast, lunch, snacks, and dinners five times a day, which is a basic principle of good nutrition", says one survey report.
No breakfast and no meatballs for dinner .
Experts point out that healthy development requires a few basic things, such as having breakfast at the same time as a family.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school families eat at the same time.
In most families, each family member eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that's been found is that one-tenth of the population doesn't eat breakfast at all.
However, breakfast is the basis of a healthy daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that families with obese children tend to eat unhealthy fries.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
Over 40% of the children surveyed play sports regularly but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Get your food ready.
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own meals from options offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating".
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is the high preference for sugary lemonades", says the survey.
For lunch, pasta took first place right before white meat.
The children did not want starchy food at all and preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Aim for health
The survey also showed that children are willing to change their habits from the moment they receive ad hoc information.
"A follow-up of a group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the 'Obesity is not a coincidence' awareness-raising session showed a strong desire to move towards a healthy diet", the survey results state.
The most striking example was the sugary lemonade, where children began to prefer drinking water.
The children most often ticked the questionnaire for white meat and fish as the main course and would cut down on sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech speciality of bread-meal balls or potatoes).
