The new installment subtitled The Run generated high expectations before its release.
He promised to take a new direction with the already aging Need for Speed racing series and to bring out a kind of game from the playable parts that would not count only on points.
So we were curious about how the extra passages would be where the main character gets out of his car and does whatever he wants.
As is already done in the NFS series, the result is completely different from what was expected.
These are potentially arcade racing games but the whole thing is pulling down because of some unnecessary bugs that have already been around for several years.
These are not really errors but rather the expression of incomprehensible laziness on the part of the developers.
The adventure starts off well.
You are caught up in an adventure where the main hero Jack has character problems and to solve them starts racing illegally across America.
You get behind the wheel on the West Coast in San Francisco and your mission is to get to New York first.
The idea has some interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than 50 races.
As a result, each race is run on a different route and the stages are planned in different environments which are quite distinct from each other and are interesting.
The player does not feel for a moment that the game is offering him something identical.
Some environments are also quite nice even if the graphic level is the same as the previous series.
Well, it's not the end of the world.
But driving through the desert, through autumn scenery, or through snow-capped mountains is very pleasing to the eye.
The tests are also occasionally supplemented by an atypical element.
For example, in the desert, you find yourself in a sandstorm that significantly reduces your visibility.
Then in the mountains you have to be careful that an avalanche doesn't fall on you.
Besides, the different races are well arranged one behind the other.
There are only a few of them, but that's enough.
One moment you are trying to outrun the required number of opponents (as in a classic race) and then you are running against the clock (a classic clock duel) and then you are facing another duel with an opponent.
Now and then you also have the police coming in and trying to make things difficult for you.
The new feature is the off-vehicle passages.
It's more of an interactive animation where most of the time Jack is running from someone and you have to help him by tapping the right button at the right time.
It's not complicated.
What is surprising is that there are fewer such moments than you would expect (to be specific there are only three).
The result is just that, because this element is not likely to interfere and is, in the context described above, among the elements that enhance the game.
The driving pattern is in the tradition of the previous games.
Which means that there's nothing out of the ordinary right now, but we can't say it's negative.
As for the realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But although you can find better in competition the driving model goes very well with the type of racing design.
So it's all right.
The problems start to show up after a while.
The driving pattern is different, the collision pattern is not yet developed.
We don't expect this game to have complicated deformation and collisions, but when you don't have, in a collision with any object, the slightest idea of how your car behaves, so it's not completely good.
During tight overtaking you sometimes touch each other slightly but otherwise your car starts to go into a frenzy.
Or it's going to be in pieces.
Thanks to the reboot system, it's not really a problem but it really annoys you.
The restart is done so that when you break your face or you step out into the scene the game takes you back to the moment of the last point on the route.
But you only have five reboots.
When you've used all five reboots you have to start the game all over again.
So it's more of a tool, in case something goes wrong, than something you can really rely on.
Sometimes restarting does not help and the solution must be found by recalling the route in question.
The great thing about this game is that the same stocks end up in the same places.
For example, there are certain corners that you have to go through in a certain way or else it doesn't go through.
Otherwise you will always find "civilian" vehicles in the same configuration at a given place, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds early or one minute late.
What's annoying is situations where you see the other car pass easily between two cars coming in the opposite direction and when you arrive, you have to either pull over and go around them or brake.
It doesn't matter if you go to meet him because it's calculated so that for any given situation he always comes right up to your nose.
Opponents have other advantages.
Throughout the game, you arrive at certain places, again without regard to the time, and you always have the same opponent ahead of you in the same place.
It's most annoying at the end of the game when you're driving on a long bridge in the opposite direction.
The enemy must pass before you at all costs.
When it passes in front of you, it hides the view of other vehicles in the opposite direction and you crash into it quite a few times.
You can understand that the goal of this game is to do something exciting and full of adrenaline, but it's clear that you get bored quickly.
And that's a shame because through a simple driving model the game is interesting and the places with so much action that you don't have time to follow everything that happens.
And it doesn't matter if it's because of the concept of 50 unique routes, the order of the races is such that there's no chance of getting bored or something.
The original idea was to change cars during races.
You have to be careful at the gas stations on the routes because you can change cars there, but most of the time you can just use the one you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are ideal for cities, large American cars for straight highways and super sports cars with exotic outfits on very technical roads, for example on mountain laces.
And the challenge mode, which is racing in particular places that you know of as adventure, goes very well with the main story mode.
You not only receive medals but also experience points that add to your profile which is common to challenges and adventure.
When you reach the highest level of driver, various objects begin to unlock:
It connects online with the Autolog function which, among other things, compares your results with those of other players and provides you with other functions in the community.
One of the hardest shots to understand is the situation in the final race of the adventure.
You drive your car into the subway tunnel (this looks like) where you drive in the dark on the tracks (this looks like).
Your speedometer tells you 150 to 200 kilometers per hour (a priori) and behind you comes a subway train that sends your car straight to the scrap yard.
At the editorial office we had a discussion for a few days about whether anyone really thought about creating this game or whether the authors really think we are idiots.
The technical part of the game is not great, but the visual part is generally pleasant and in some cases really great.
What's disturbing is that in more extreme situations, the imagery doesn't keep up and in some cases tragically.
This is especially true of accidents with a large number of participants when a fluid imaging is no longer useful.
The soundtrack is good and the track is a choice.
In order to appeal to the largest possible number of people, and especially the youngest, a new soundtrack has been created in the style of "I mix everything", but it can be expected that no one will buy the game for the music.
The general impression of Need for Speed: The Run is really confusing.
If the game didn't have these stupid mistakes we could say without fear that this is the best NFS production in recent years.
But this game feels like it's not over.
Fun is really nice, but be prepared for mistakes to hit you in the eye with the force of an airfield reflector.
The Velvet Students in concert with the Charles University Choirs
The Festa Academica festival is offering for the third time festivities that link the International Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical part.
During the festival, 20 choirs from high schools and secondary schools perform.
The festival's highlight is two concerts on 17 November.
"Charles University has a big part in this festival".
"Among the choirs is the Choir of the Faculty of Education and Humanities, and the festival committee is headed by the rector, Vaclav Hampl", says Jakub Calou, head of the organizing team.
The highlight of the festival is the concert of the Choir of High Schools and Secondary Schools, which is held with free admission on 17 November from 2 pm on the space in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The programme includes the composition of the well-known Czech jazzman Karel Ruzicka, Celebration Jazz mass.
In the evening, the concert "Students in Velvet" takes place at the National House in Vinohrady, with choirs from the universities and Charles University.
The aim of the Festa Academica is not only to celebrate with dignity the International Students' Day and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present the audience with choir music of the highest level and to develop the creative cooperation of young people.
The main organiser is the Czech Cheese Union in cooperation with the Jan Kepler High School.
The whole action is under the auspices of Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of Prague and Vaclav Hampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival takes place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The programme also offers high-level concerts, musical events, student events and other activities.
All information can be found on the festival's website www.festaacademica.cz.
