The history of IBM: from slices of cheese to space flight.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, originally under the complicated name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially a trademark used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 1980s.
They had technology such as the old "pointers", the clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 chaired the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the firm's founder - Watson's ideas are still the basis of the company's identity and culture.
Watson took over the Kusqu's firm in 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, started with the production of every machine possible for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, sales multiplied to $9 million and the firm began to expand to all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable to the firm that after 40 years as head of the firm his son Thomas Watson Jr. took over as chairman.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM people and computers helped NASA guide spaceflight -- to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 to the Moon.
Meanwhile in 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that set the standard for computers at the time, the IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to deal in consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that's been successful at IBM for the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept.
The aim is to make intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
In the area of commerce, IBM has recently developed a 'Smarter Commerce' platform that helps salespeople manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history in our territory as well.
It opened its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe at the time.
Today, besides IBM RT, there is also the Brno strategic outsourcing centre.
The Central and Eastern European Centre is based in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team for speech recognition.
