How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered tours mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists were on holiday in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then the regime began to lean westward and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (including Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed an invitation letter otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at this time also offered trips to the West, however you had to stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't won yet.
The currency agreement which was a condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currency (Western currency) for travel to the West.
The Czechs spent most of their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit continues to this day.
Since 1989, the Czech travel industry has undergone a major revolution.
Although holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak until 1989, Czechs spent 4 million holiday days abroad in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to travel freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the western neighbouring countries has led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria, Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovaks could not for long fly to the West, which everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel agencies made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income was not enough to pay for a hotel or a boarding house.
The typical trait of a Czech traveller at that time was to take with him his own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was the exchangeability of the Czech kr√≥na, which finally allowed our tourists to buy Western currency freely after decades.
Our standard of living and average wage have increased, which led to another important moment around 1997.
The increasing demand for travel has led travel agencies to start planning tours with charter flights since 1997, which have been considerably cheaper than before thanks to contracts.
In the late 1990s the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually all the developed countries in the world except the US which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism was when the first charter flight to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as every year, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
Over 100,000 Czechs visit these exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the group of developed countries.
In 2008 too, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time ever spent more than 15 000 kroner per person on holidays abroad including the associated costs.
The General Assembly must find its President but it may end in a situation without a solution
Almost five months have passed since Czech football was without a president and there is a risk that the successor to Ivan Hasek as head of the Czech Football Association will not yet be known after another general assembly to be held in Nymburk on Thursday.
However, there is still no agreement on which voting procedure to follow.
Without this agreement it is not possible to start voting for one of the three candidates.
Jindrich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomas Paclik are interested in the Czech football management.
Hasek resigned in June and during his departure called on his colleagues to unite and find a strong personality who will lead football in the future.
Only during the era after Hasek did football return to divergences between the chambers of the Association which could not agree on a common candidate.
This was fully demonstrated on 16 September when a new president had to be elected.
The delegates of the General Assembly met in vain in the National House in Prague because the negotiations were blocked and there was not even a discussion on how to vote.
There was no agreement on who had the right to vote at the General Assembly - only, it seems, the statutory representatives or the fully-authorized officials.
On this one point there has since been a partial agreement, with the help of the Bureau for State and Law, that representation on the basis of full power is not possible.
Disagreements still persist over the rules of procedure for the election.
It is all too clear that the Executive Committee, which in its planned or extraordinary negotiations has also made no contribution to the situation.
Opinions on the possibility of voting have changed several times but the key point remains the same.
The question is, how do we proceed on the third round so as not to fall in the trap?
"The key to the dispute is that either we follow the statutes or we find another model", said one of the three vice-presidents of the Czech Football Association, Dusan Svoboda, who represents professional football in the association.
The rules of the proposed model state that the candidate who receives the highest percentage of votes in the chamber for which he is running wins the third round.
Moravia is reportedly ready to withdraw so that the candidate who receives the highest percentage of the votes in both chambers wins.
And the Czech side is considering the condition that the winner should have at least two-thirds of the voting percentage.
"Only then would the idea of two previous rounds be lost and the bicameral concept completely rejected", admits Svoboda, who understands the Moravian Party's objections and who believes it would be best not to change the rules of procedure and to vote according to the current statutes.
It is surprising that Tomas Paclik also agrees even though he believes that the electoral rules established by the statutes benefit the most Pelta of all the candidates.
"I want the votes to be as strict as possible in accordance with the articles of association".
"So that there are no more crazy ideas from a representative like in past general meetings", said the owner of Victoria Plzen, who is a first-time candidate and who in his presentations has been mainly against Pelta.
Pelta is still optimistic.
He said that Nymburk would have a new President and that the candidates would work together constructively in the future.
"The possible qualification for the European Championship today should calm everyone down".
"Football will be on a happy wave again and there will be more enthusiasm for cooperation", adds the Jablonec official, who among the three has the most experience in managing both professional and regional football.
Rajchl is more pessimistic.
"I believe in this agreement but unfortunately the situation is very tense".
"This is not a problem between Czechs and Moravians, but there are tendencies to change the drawing rules".
"This could cause another deadlock at the General Assembly".
"I still hope that common sense will win", said Rajchl.
