The most beautiful swimming pools in Europe
A leap in the blue
By Julia Stanek
UFO-optic paddles, beautiful swimming pools in Budapest: Travelers across Europe can experience the blue miracle - and after circling the city or taking a long walk - can rest their tired legs in hot tub waters.
A book shows which swimming pool can experience the most well-being.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip for the last 18 months, there was one item that should not be missing from her luggage: her swimsuit.
Lying on her back in the water, she observed the artistically arranged domes, and swam up against the putten marbles that waited for her on the other side of the pool and never failed to admire the meticulously restored Art Nouveau of these converted pools.
If she liked an indoor pool, she would promptly write down in her notebook all the interesting details about the type of building and its history.
More than 200 pools have been surveyed in this way by architectural historian Meder and she has presented them in her already published book: "Badefreuden" (Bath Joys).
She has led her "trips to the most exceptional baths of Central Europe" in 13 countries. Besides Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she has visited places in Italy, France, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland and a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia respectively.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
Meder explains that she has little interest in sports but is drawn to water in a totally different way.
