The Pavilion that Moved
The Commission has not yet adopted a decision on the application of this Regulation.
An architectural story with ups and downs and a happy ending: the Austrian pavilion for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition won prizes, was a museum in Vienna, then sat empty and fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and is an exhibition house.
If you are enthusiastic about postwar modern architecture, its clear shapes, glass hangars, bold, vibrant look and new building materials that are typical of belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World Exhibition is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix of Architecture" for its lightweight, suspended, steel and glass construction.
The building is considered to this day an important milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian World Exhibition.
With its legendary four-cylinder BMW house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His design of the pavilion as a temporary building had been exhibited after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the artwork on, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for as long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has become increasingly dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it is now called the "21st Century House" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opened the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every way.
The new start was completed by Agn√®s Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belv√©d√®re.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career including in her youth as an artistic skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, she particularly successfully carried out transformation work with politicians and monument protection, she obtained public and private sponsorship funds and established the operation.
Apart from contemporary art, works by the sculptor Fritz Wotruba, whose foundation bears the same name, have been exhibited there, a caf√© and a bookstore are located there, and an office is to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the production Krischanitz was therefore the ideal performer.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded the secession of Joseph Olbracht and had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost its generosity and lightness after it moved to Vienna and changed its use.
The current transformations had major problems: the building was "an energy gap", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was laid and the roof replaced with special safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges have been reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled covers have been rehabilitated.
Two basements made way for the new farm, a dimmed light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it's almost new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in a rust-protective red-brown tint.
And the theater is even exactly the same as it was.
All this under close supervision of the relevant monuments authorities and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and cheap had to be found, and that also appeal to the Office of Monuments Protection", says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a raw ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building has remained flexible and light.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz said recently, a typical "Drop-in-the-City" story.
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and yet wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the 21st century house is not in the wrong place, because if it is a lucky urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands the newly planned "central station district", with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck may come: the 21st century house could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
