Walls have eyes: researchers study you on Facebook
Before he became the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just a guy sharing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to being caught in a murderous frenzy in Norway in July leaving 77 victims, faced his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being in cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media sites.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers are eager to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy... log in to Facebook.
"We realised that it wasn't that hard to find them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is so full of personal information, Jamie Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they're looking for with scientific accuracy - the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team found that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. They targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to participate in a survey. The questions asked were about their education level, their attitudes towards violence and their optimism about their own future.
By connecting with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"It's a new way of doing research", says Jamie Bartlett.
Some of the results are not at all surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly men, young people and anti-immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who combine online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens".
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new indispensable tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that touch on health issues like social trends, through likes, wall posts and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, the 'data supernova' is driving an explosion in search, increasing the number of research papers with the site's name in the title by almost 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach on the street.
"Before, when you tried to survey people in the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You had to go to the party, but they would never let you in", says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all of this - you have direct access to their information".
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and treat health and social problems.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and colleagues, young college students who shared their drunken exploits on Facebook were far more likely to be alcoholic than students who did not.
Megan Moreno suggests that students' colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to help in the event a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
"You can't treat a problem if you don't diagnose it", says Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington.
"We know how to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be identified".
Facebook also constantly gains access to user information.
The site's data team studied statistics on dating and Valentine's Day, turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (based on information only available - champions of digital freedom have long argued that the site could make its data treasure available to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed access to your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey they haven't even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines for how to gather information other than through the Internet, online is a very different matter.
"I don't think a lot of users have ever thought about the fact that a researcher could look at their profile", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, based on a 2006 study he conducted by looking at his students' Facebook walls.
"As far as they knew, the exchanges were only seen by their friends".
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even without an Internet connection, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study will be completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know the truth of a user's profile or wall.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in real life are two completely different things", says Neil Selwyn.
That's why, despite his background as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notepad and a pen are still the best tools you can use.
"Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people", he says.
"Social studies is supposed to be about social issues - and social issues are not about computers".
