7 lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview at the movies this week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - a technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans may find most telling in a recently found interview with Steve Jobs that will be released this week as the first part of a movie in major markets, is how much this creative mind had understood the processes and workflows of products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified himself as a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a chart improver - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease that leaves them thinking that a great idea does 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which chronicled the birth of the computer, and he sat down for over an hour with Steve Jobs for a long, rare conversation.
At that time, it had been about 10 years since Steve Jobs had to leave Apple, and he was already hard at work on his new computer company NeXT, aiming for a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies were lost in transport.
It wasn't until after Steve Jobs died that a complete video was found in the director's garage.
This video, slightly edited, is the basis of the 68-minute film, Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be released in theaters next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
At four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in an effort to provide a precise answer.
We also find moments where Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, elbowing him to get him to speed up and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, there's a strangely prescient aspect to Lost Interview where Steve Jobs evaluates what he sees as good or bad about other companies and shares his own vision for the future of computing.
It's one thing to read the posthumous reviews of Steve Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then he puts them into practice.
Here's a quick recap of seven remarkable scenes from Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"All these years, I've always asked, 'Why do you do things?' and the answers are always the same: 'Oh, simply because you have to do them.'"
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to give details of his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Confused as to how costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" assessed at face value and then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory which ensured the precise calculation of commercial costs.
On the possibility of playing a trick on the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack into phone networks and make free long-distance calls.
The device has been the subject of much writing beforehand, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a pay phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We would wrap the ball in different things a half dozen times and you would yell into the pay phone and it would happen to you a minute later on the pay phone next door", Jobs laughs.
"We were young, and through this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We didn't know much, but we were able to invent a little thing that could control big things, and it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs goes on to tell of a wonderful trick that he and Wozniak devised: he telephoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night posing as Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several Catholic hierarchs are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go out laughing madly just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett's approach):
At the age of 12, while hunting for parts to make a frequency meter, he looked up Bill Hewlett's number in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated".
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company's Palo Alto research labs, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed".
It was the size of a suitcase, had a little cathode ray tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a whim.
Early in his career, while he was selling printed circuit boards, a customer asked him to assemble a complete computer.
He was only given 30 days' credit to assemble and deliver the finished devices.
Later at Apple, he recalled the difficulties he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big arguments . . . people yelling at me that it would take me five years [to make a $300 mouse].
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for 15 dollars and it was incredibly reliable.
About the big companies that are dying:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would make mistakes and lose control of their market share.
"Suppose you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing can change it, so [these types of people] end up running companies and product people are left out of decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who can't imagine designing a good product versus a bad product - the manual labor required.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the '90s.
They've wrested defeat from victory.
On innovation as an art form:
"A huge amount of manual work separates a great idea from a great product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows".
You learn a lot about its intricacies.
There are tradeoffs to be made -- some things you can't do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep a thousand things in mind (these concepts) by putting them together.
And finally, the decisions are made by personal taste, and it's about trying to expose yourself to the best products that humans have created, and trying to bring those things into the product that you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We're always ashamed to steal great ideas.
And that's part of what makes the Macintosh exceptional, because the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who just happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren't for computer science, they would have done some amazing things in another field.
Scalia and Thomas dining with health care law opponents as the court sits
On the day the Supreme Court is meeting behind closed doors to consider the issue of political discord, whether opposition to President Obama's health care law will be heard, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were spotted at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will be defending the case before the high court.
The event took place last Thursday, when the nine judges met for a conference to discuss petitions for review.
One of the cases in question involved a lawsuit brought by 26 states challenging the ambitious health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying point for conservative activists nationwide.
The judges agreed to hear the complaint, as a monumental argument at 5:30 is expected next March, and the outcome will likely be likely to further destabilize the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court ruling is issued.
The lawyer who will stand before the court and argue for the rejection of the law is likely to be Paul Clement, who served as Solicitor General of the United States under the administration of George W. Bush.
Clement's law firm, PLLC Bancroft, was one of two dozen firms that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a long-standing group dedicated to advocating conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the business associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another promoter was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial stake in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel a few hours after the court conference on the case.
Among them was Mitch McConnell, a top Republican in the Senate and a vocal opponent of the health care bill.
The star guests at the dinner?
This is not new. Both judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And there's nothing that goes against ethics.
In fact, judges are exempt from the code of conduct that governs the actions of federal judges.
If they were, they would probably argue by the Canon 4C code, which states: "A judge may attend fundraisers of law-related and other organizations although the judge may not be a speaker, guest of honor, or be on the program of such an event".
Nevertheless, the mere presence of Scalia and Thomas in close proximity to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a massive financial interest, was enough to alarm government ethics activists.
"This violation of ethics and a flagrant disregard for the code contradicts several judges' statements that the Court follows the same rules as all other federal judges", said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"Judges were drinking and dining and at a fundraising gala with lawyers who have cases pending in court".
Their presence and participation in the fundraising for this event disproves any claim to impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas showed little regard for critics claiming that they were too easily mixing court business with the agenda of groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a high-profile conservative activist.
And the conservatives are claiming that it's Justice Elena Kagan who has an ethics problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan was general counsel for the Obama administration when the first objections to the law were brought to the trial court level.
Her critics pressured Kagan to decline to hear the case, saying she had invested too much in defending the law to be impartial.
Kagan gave no indication that she would.
Boeing records record $18 billion in airliner orders
Emirates has ordered 50 Boeing 777 twin-aisle airliners, with the option to buy 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliners to Oman Air, a deal estimated to be worth more than $1 billion.
It is not unusual for a company to receive an order for 50 of its products.
But it is a big deal when the company in question is the Boeing aircraft manufacturer and the 50 planes have reached a record $18 billion.
Equally amazing is where Boeing got this order from: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In a forecast published Monday, the Chicago-based airline estimates that airlines in the Middle East will need 2,520 planes worth a total of $450 billion over the next 20 years.
Over the weekend, Boeing announced the most expensive commercial aircraft order in its history - 50 Boeing 777s with two-aisle flights.
It was Emirates Airlines based in Dubai that placed the order.
Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Airshow that the airline is also likely to buy 20 more aircraft, bringing the total order amount to $26 billion.
On the other hand, Boeing said Monday that Oman Air has ordered six Boeing 787-8s, dubbed Dreamliners, a model that boasts significant fuel savings and passenger convenience.
The total value of these six aircraft is over a billion dollars.
"This is clearly very positive for Boeing", said Neal Dihora, an analyst at Morningstar.
"These customers in particular are of immense value".
In the Middle East, oil producing countries own many of their airlines.
So not only can they afford these planes, but a rise in the price of fuel - usually detrimental to the airlines because it is their biggest expense - would not be so detrimental to them since the country would make money from the rise in oil prices.
This is important because these airlines will be less likely than others to cancel or postpone their aircraft orders when oil prices rise, Dihora said.
"They have a natural risk cover", he said.
The order from Emirates strengthens Boeing's dominance in the large-sized aircraft market and helps to curb the attempted encroachment by competitor Airbus with its A350 aircraft.
Boeing's victory at the air show comes four months after Airbus announced it was postponing the debut of the larger version of the A350, which competes directly with the Boeing 777-300ER.
Airbus is postponing its start-up to increase its momentum following customer demand for increased cargo capacity and range.
Boeing shares rose 1.5% to $67.94.
