The BASD urges Asia to help the euro area
The Asian Development Bank has asked India and China to prepare to help the euro area get out of the sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term decline that would impede the development of the Asian economy.
Rajat Nag, the managing director of the Manila-based BASD, said the world's two fastest growing economic powers must "do everything in their power" to speed up the recovery of the currency area through the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements.
He warned the BRICs (Brazil, Russia, India, China) against looking at Europe's difficulties with an "indifferent eye" and pointed out that Asian financial support alongside European leaders and resources would help avoid a long-term collapse of the world economy.
"We are all in this together".
"So anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is useful", he told the Financial Times in an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia may be protected to a certain extent but it is not immune".
"So if China and India can help, let nothing stop them".
In recent months, the euro area has been seriously shaken by a sovereign debt crisis.
Recently, the cost of Italy's debt has skyrocketed dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The burgeoning sovereign debt crisis in Europe has raised fears that the world economy is heading for recession, and has prompted calls from major emerging economies to come together to help the euro area find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that the IMF would provide all Asian aid, but he also said that this bilateral assistance - such as buying bonds from the US financial rescue fund, the European Financial Stability Fund - gave greater negotiating power to Europe's Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, the Indian Minister of Commerce and Industry, said that "India will do everything it can" to help the eurozone as its own economy now suffers from falling exports and a drying in of foreign capital.
"Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and turbulent", he said.
"We have monumental challenges to meet and we must maintain a high level of growth".
"This is not a choice, it's an imperative, because where would we find jobs for tens of millions of our young men and women?"
Others argue that developing economies such as India should not help rich Europeans as they face their own major economic challenges.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the United States, said it would be politically very difficult to get Europe to accept aid for the 1.2 billion Indians, at least 800,000 of whom live on $2 a day or less.
"One day they will find out that Greeks retire at 50 and go on holiday in the sun and they will have a hard time swallowing it", he said.
Lee Howell, the chairman of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India's reserves should be used to keep many well-paid Greek civil servants in mismanaged and loss-making jobs, such as in the railway sector.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis was likely to have "significant repercussions" across Asia.
BASD's forecast of 7.5% economic growth in Asia in 2011/2012 now faces "risk of loss" due to the European threat.
He said vulnerable emerging markets needed to develop "rescue plans" to protect themselves from economic upheaval and large capital outflows.
Severe warnings from the Pentagon about potential defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta stepped up pressure on Congress Monday, warning that imminent automatic budget cuts would undermine national security, triggering a financial chain reaction from the Pentagon corridors to the battlefields of Afghanistan to civilian gatherings.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts for the next decade, but now fears that an additional $600 or more of cuts are imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
"The impacts of these cuts would be devastating to the department", Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Ariz., and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said that failure by Congress to reach a budget agreement resulting in what is called a sequestration would result in 23% cuts as well as the freezing of many new projects.
"Such a large reduction, applied indiscriminately, would render most of our ships and construction projects unfeasible - you cannot buy three quarters of a ship or a building - and seriously undermine other modernization efforts", Panetta wrote to the senators.
"We would also be forced to part with a number of our civilian staff and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we would almost certainly have to send civilians on unpaid leave in order to achieve the objective".
"These changes would undermine the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our readiness".
The cuts would eventually affect the fighting troops, Panetta continues.
"Although the wartime financing of the contingency operations accounts abroad is not directly affected by the sequester, the war effort would be adversely affected by the severe disruptions in basic budgets", warned Panetta.
"Contracting personnel would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and oversight of contracts that support the war".
"Wage managers would be reduced, resulting in delays in payment to war suppliers, and legal and political support would be disrupted".
Both senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details on the potential impact of automatic compression on the Department of Defense.
"The consequence of a sequester on the Department of Defense would trigger a rapid decline of the United States as the undisputed world leader in military power".
"We are fiercely opposed to this draconian action", the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when Panetta's letter was published.
"It is not a consequence we can live with, and it is certainly not one we should impose on ourselves".
"The seizure is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen".
Whether Panetta's letter and recent warnings from senators increase pressure for a budget compromise or a call to exempt the Pentagon from cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly vocal about possible cuts, even though he himself rose to the top of the Pentagon after years of budget expertise in Congress and the White House and knowing he was faced with tough choices.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a grim picture of what could happen - a soldier with a shell, but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors".
"This is a bullet-free brigade".
"It's a fighter jet, with no trained pilots".
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that don't have enough trained soldiers to accomplish the mission", Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a depressed force, ill-prepared and unable to face potential adversaries".
"In fact, it invites aggression.. "
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifically stated how further reductions could "generate significant operational risks: delay in responding to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits on our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and unacceptable assumed risk in future combat operations".
And Panetta said that some of the biggest defense projects could go to the ground, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
This list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new littoral combat ship, and the new field vehicle, which would replace the Army and Navy Humvee.
Stopping development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its proponents say it is a critical step in improving and responding to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Spot a Lie
A glance at recent headlines shows how pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women, each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and shaken countries.
Congressman Anthony Weiner of New York and Internet celebrity, has been passed off as an idiot for quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to his coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, no one who has lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton started by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
There are many stories of cheating on school and college tests.
There have been cases where teachers have given test answers to students in order to make themselves look good on their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
Studies show that on any given day, you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are godly lies.
Another study found that people lie to each other an average of three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting or spotting lies is a vital skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game like, say, charades, where the goal is to shout, "I've got you", cheat detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data gathered over the past six decades by prestigious universities that have conducted extensive research on such projects, including psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don't stutter, blush, or get all worked up.
This does not mean that liars are hard to detect and unmask.
A trained lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, the micro-expressions of the face, the formation of the question and the time taken to respond.
I've spent several years reviewing scientific findings across the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it's clear that deception detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or management.
Good liars are skilled at reading others, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively sensing how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies while women tell more "other-centered" lies - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "set the data benchmarks".
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Watch the posture of your subject, the laughter, the quality of your voice.
You need to know if someone normally moves his feet all the time so that you don't make unfair accusations when you see him moving his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for signs of verbal and nonverbal deception.
Consider these clues red flags, not evidence of deception.
Cheating people may immobilize their upper body when they try to remember their story, they may point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or present post-interview relief -- an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions are over.
Interviewers often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
So be careful about the vocabulary of your subject.
Famous Scott Peterson went rogue by using the past while claiming his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national manhunt to find her.
Deceivers may also use distant language, such as "I did not have sex with this woman... Ms. Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
One may use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question, "Well... to be honest... if I remember correctly... as far as I know".
This makes the response perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but it is possible to develop the skills to recognize deception.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding being victimized by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
The controversial pipeline plan will be derailed after the threat of late US approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a pipeline project between Canada and the Gulf of Mexico - sparking union anger while appeasing environmentalists - the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is ready to redirect the project to get it back on track.
TransCanada said Monday night that it will move the proposed pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive area of the Nebraska dunes, and is confident that the project will still win approval.
The company announced the decision at a press conference at the Nebraska State Capitol.
TransCanada official Alex Pourbax says the company remains confident that it will eventually get approval for an oil pipeline, but with a different route.
This follows the State Department's announcement last week that it would delay its decision to grant a federal permit for the project until it receives further studies of potential routes to avoid the Nebraska Dunes and Ogallala aquifer areas, which are vast underground water sources.
"This is a real way forward", Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska, told Fox News.
The new environmental review commissioned by the State Department would likely have delayed any decision until 2013, after next year's election, though officials deny any political involvement in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the State Department's decision, and expressed his support.
The 2,735-kilometer pipeline would run from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would transport 700,000 barrels a day from the province of Alberta to the refineries in Texas.
To do that, he would have to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists but loved by working groups, who have bet on the estimated 20,000 jobs linked to the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan are pushing for a law to force the removal of the Sand Hills area and the Ogallala aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department's ongoing environmental impact study found that the project would only have limited negative environmental impacts, but the energy industry said the department's inspector general ordered a separate investigation of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is that a lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was a campaign adviser to Hillary Clinton in 2008, would represent a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a company that was hired to conduct the original study was an inappropriate choice because of its relationship with TransCanada.
Patti LaBelle is being sued for allegedly causing a young child to vomit in fear.
A New York family says that disco diva Patti LaBelle's outburst of violence in the lobby of their Manhattan apartment building has terrified their little girl to the point of vomiting in fear.
The singer's "Lady Marmalade" tirade frightened 18-month-old Genevieve Monk to the point that she suffered "personality changes, sleep problems" and "increased fear of strangers", her family said during the Manhattan Supreme Court trial.
It was November 10th of last year when stage technician Kevin Monk, his wife, a kindergarten teacher, Roseanna, and Genevieve were preparing to go on a family trip.
While Kevin Monk was getting his car, Roseanna Monk came down the hallway of their Riverside Boulevard building with their luggage, carrying Genevieve in her arms.
Roseanna Monk said she stopped by the door and laid her daughter down for a moment.
"Someone came up behind me and said, 'Do you know what your daughter does?' I said, 'Yes,' and I went to get her", she said.
LaBelle angrily rebuked the pregnant woman.
"She said in a very aggressive tone, 'You shouldn't leave your daughter by the door,'" says Roseanna Monk.
I said, "I don't care what you say or think".
She became enraged and started using swear words - the word "and" and "and" out loud...
She had a bottle of water and started pouring water from the bottle on me.
She said that at this point, Genevieve became hysterical.
"I said to this woman, 'Look what you did to my daughter,'" said the child's mother.
LaBelle threw herself on the mother - who was still holding Genevieve - and had to be held up by her entourage who dragged her to a waiting car, says Roseanna Monk.
The little girl was crying so hard that she started vomiting, she adds.
Later, the family sent a note apologizing to LaBelle, but received no response.
LaBelle's lawyer and representatives have not returned our calls for comment.
The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages, but the family's lawyer, Sam Davis, said he took the case for free and the family plans to donate all the money received to a children's cancer charity.
"The goal is to hold Patti LaBelle accountable for her conduct", Davis said.
"This kind of behavior is totally unacceptable, especially to a kindergarten teacher carrying an 18-month-old child".
The climate crisis has slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario L√≥pez Valdez's administration, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment declined and the economy contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the government of Mario L√≥pez Valdez, self-proclaimed of change, which generated great expectations regarding the progress of the economy, but given the climatic adversity at the beginning of the year, the rise is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
