Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to perform one of their best shows yet next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have been waiting for over 20 years, but the band says that for them too, it will be a dream come true to perform in this country.
That's what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The band is on the South American side of their two-decade tour and on Sunday 20th will make their only stop in Central America.
On that day they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 pm, alongside the Los Angeles band The X and the Las Robertas nationals.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Naci√≥n on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican fans, Pearl Jam's performance in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So we're excited to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live intensely the days before.
What's your message to your most ardent followers?
Thank you for sticking by us all these years.
It took us 21 years to get to Costa Rica, so thank you for waiting so long and we're sorry that it took so long to get to this concert.
Some people are already saying that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've put on in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We gave two huge shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that it's put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to performing there.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle, and Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world for both.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf, and that's how we learned it, from people who like to surf.
Seeing the tour, you've given huge shows, with lots of songs.
What did you plan on doing for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never performed there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We'll try to do the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we'll try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never rehearse the repertoire.
What is the reason for this?
I think part of the reason is because we have nine records and we can perform over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, which is why it's very difficult to choose which songs to perform each night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved those songs and that we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you're celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all you've accomplished?
Yes, I certainly did.
First of all, I think none of us imagined that we were going to form a great rock band, and the fact that we've been doing it for over 20 years makes it sound like a dream.
We continue to talk about our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together is very exciting.
We love each other and we love making music.
We're lucky to be going to places in the world we've always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a fundamental part in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great groups.
We're very close friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's surprising when a movement starts out from a group of friends and is unusual.
Occasionally, a group emerges from a city, but it's much stranger when five or ten groups emerge from the same city at once.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to still be friends with all of them and it's an honor for us to be part of this Seattle sound that came out.
It's also very strange that a group like yours can stay together and with the same members for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that's a lot longer than most bands normally last.
First, I believe we are all lucky to be alive, and second, we all care about others.
We're all close friends and because of that there are music boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't get any better.
Your relationship with the word "celebrity" has not been easy, but your success has allowed you to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we got older, it became easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don't spend too much time on tour because it's easy to fall into this game of big crowds and people who like your music.
If you don't forget that people are here for music, it helps you remember that you have to respect music and what it has brought, not to think about the fact that you're famous and a rock star, which none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn't release a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration with the fact that it lasted so short and the most important thing is the fact that we're still very good friends with Bruce and Greg who started in the band with us and when I listen to a song or I see a picture I think about the amazing person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to work, laugh, talk about music and football and many other things with him.
He was a surprising human being and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yeah, the production sent us videos with different suggestions and this was the band we liked the most, so we're excited to see what Las Robertas can offer live and it should be very entertaining.
Why do you always change Yello Ledbetter's lyrics live?
This is a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he does it with the first words he thinks of.
As a bass player, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Some of the first ones I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge up despite the fact that it's out of fashion?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and if it's relevant now, I think that's wonderful, because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making the best music ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It's interesting, because I think there are some songs on the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that are classified as very dark songs, even though they can sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's a trauma in your life and you lose a parent or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and these songs, no doubt, represent that for me.
I also think that you can be happy and even then you can make dark music.
