The asphalt of the UNAM would avoid the clogs
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signs of the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 paving stones each rainy season in the Valle de M√©xico Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera N√°jera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who said that if the process of building and maintaining the tarpaulin is adequate, the paving stones could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his lecture A Technological Opinion on Crushed Stone, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he heads was developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with similar properties to asphalt but with greater mechanical strength at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera N√°jera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and therefore the formation of cinders.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a combination of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight called asphaltenes, and molecules with a lower molecular weight called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt is that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that the asphalt strength on the streets is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineer.
The QF researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de M√©xico were mostly covered with flexible paving, made up of six layers of material, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the little stones that make up the layer, he pointed out, is washed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating forces, it allows the forces to spread very well through the pavement.
If the asphalt was modified, the asphalt would spread better, the chemical engineer said.
"On the asphalt layer", he said, "they put a last layer called the rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt".
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the bearing layer also requires that it be of adequate thickness and that the material of which it is made be carefully selected.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer and it is difficult for it to get out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and consequently causes the screeching.
In the process of formation of a ridge, he says, the first to break down is the rolling film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of slopes and therefore the thickness of each layer of pavement must always be related to the vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent slopes.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to research and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow for the repair of the casings easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
