The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
The two countries are losing some of their power, and it is becoming harder for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to cut off access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But this is at the cost of a weakened energy Europe, since the project has created a rift between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in achieving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavy consumers of gas and whose deposits are declining.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us organically", Fillon said at the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom executives, who are present in large numbers at Lubmin, the gas terminal.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of steel and covered with concrete to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It rests on the seabed, 200 meters on average.
The construction of the tunnel was to avoid minefields from World War II.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", says Jens M√ºller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Moreover, more measures have been taken to protect the flora and fauna.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is uninterrupted on its entire length by anything: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but the project was abandoned when the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state company permanently established off their coast.
"If there is a malfunction, we stop the gas flow in less than a minute", says Jens M√ºller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline is therefore released into the air.
But this is considered unlikely by the builders who have planned the welds to leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the condition of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, towed by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus which circulates inside the pipeline.
It is shaped like a cigar, is inserted into a tube, one meter wide, and is pushed by the gas.
When it arrives, after three full days of travel at a speed of 10 feet per second, it delivers accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without any repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
It's 200 bars to go, 100 bars to go.
Five companies joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader is still Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Germany's E.ON and BASF joined the group (15.5% each), as did Gasunie from the Netherlands and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased all gas transmission capacity to this company for a renewable period of 20 years.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported", says Jens M√ºller.
The construction of the pipeline was financed 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to be EUR 7.4 billion for the two pipelines.
For example, GDF Suez invested 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure to recover their costs, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
The gas outlet is formed by 15 foot high valves.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the incoming gas before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a name tag.
Created about 15 years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine aims to bring back the taste of writing.
It smells like adventure, hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its broken white leaves, as if aged by time.
Yet the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a distinguished but design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of launching the new product.
The booklet is based on an old production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back to life an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12,7 million units sold.
We are a long way from the secret production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw a picture of the buyer, because the notebook appeals to businessmen, students and professionals alike.
Like Moleskine, his customers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, has grown to almost 100 today and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city centre and has managed to impose her identity.
"We have kept up with the times and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer cases... The brand is available in a range of supports.
A success that made envious: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for disabled people begins today.
Despite a voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is still twice the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Discouraging ?
"No", says Eric Blanchet, executive director of the Adapt, the association that organizes the Employment Week for the Disabled".
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high but three times as high".
"But there is still a lot to do".
It must be said that for the unemployed disabled there are still many obstacles to access to employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 years old (an average of 17%).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10 000 are disabled.
Finally, longterm unemployment is widespread: 53% for disabled people, compared with 38% on average.
In short, all these factors make it particularly difficult to return to work, and they "are the root of the problem", says Christian Grapin, managing director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for the objective brakes.
The fact remains that the mentality is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur for the City association indicated that managers surveyed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% for disabled workers, set in a law of 1987.
The latest known figures, from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at about 3 percent", says Pierre Blanc, executive director of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with the law.
The evidence is that the number of 'taxed' establishments, as well as the amounts paid, fell between 2007 and 2011 from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, put a lot of pressure on companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
Hazard: "What a pleasure"
